  <prompt>
    Using the caller inventory from task 040, migrate every non-chat caller of
    `AnalysisOrchestrationService.ExecuteAnalysisAsync` to `PlaybookOrchestrationService.ExecuteAsync`
    via `IInvokePlaybookAi` facade (with degenerate 3-node playbook OR consumer-routing dispatch).
    The chat-summarize caller (`SessionSummarizeOrchestrator`) is OUT of scope here — it was migrated
    by Wave 9 task 091. After this task, the only remaining reference to `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` should
    be the declaration itself (which task 042 deletes). If the caller audit (task 040) showed
    ONLY the chat-summarize caller existed, this task becomes a no-op except for the verification step
    — document that explicitly and proceed.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET backend developer migrating call sites from a legacy direct-invocation method to the
    canonical playbook orchestrator facade. Goal: every non-chat caller routes through `IInvokePlaybookAi`
    without behavior regression. Mirror the migration pattern Wave 9 task 091 established for chat-summarize.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Every non-chat caller of `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` migrated to the playbook orchestrator. Specifically:
    1. Every non-chat call site identified in task 040's audit refactored to call `IInvokePlaybookAi.InvokePlaybookAsync` (or `IConsumerRoutingService.ResolveAsync` + invoke) instead
    2. If a caller's payload was a "one-shot AI call" shape, replace with a degenerate 3-node playbook (Start → AiAnalysis → ReturnResponse) OR a named-consumer dispatch
    3. Behavior preserved: same Action/prompt invoked, same return shape parsed, same logging hooks fired
    4. Unit + integration tests for the migrated call sites updated to mock `IInvokePlaybookAi` instead of `IAnalysisOrchestrationService`
    5. `dotnet build` and `dotnet test` pass
    6. Post-task grep for `ExecuteAnalysisAsync` shows only the method declaration (and possibly test fixtures flagged for removal in task 042)
  </goal>

  <inputs>
